Lego Challenge

Data

The dataset for today gives details on price and other characteristics of 6172 Lego toy sets, including the number of Pieces and Minifigures inside and the Year they were created, as well as the Name, Theme, Subtheme and Item_Number of each set.

In case you donât know the joy of lego, below is a minifigure sitting on a vehicle made of lego bricks and pieces:

Your Challenge

Some analysis is shown below (without explanation).

  • How many problems or errors can you find?
  • For each one, do you have a suggestion as to how to fix it?
  • First, make a list of the problems/errors and brief ideas of how to fix. If you have time, start trying to implement some of your fixes.
  • At the end of group work time, submit on Moodle a copy of your work.
  • Hint: The solution will probably involve a GAMâ¦maybe with random effects.

Analysis to Critique

legos <- read_csv('https://sldr.netlify.app/data/legos.csv') |>
  mutate(Theme = factor(Theme),
         Subtheme = factor(Subtheme))
gf_boxplot(Price ~ factor(Year), 
         alpha = 0.1,
         data = legos) |>
  gf_theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 70))

gf_point(Price ~ Minifigures, 
         alpha = 0.1,
         data = legos)

gf_point(Price ~ Pieces,
         color = ~Availability,
         alpha = 0.3,
         scales = 'free',
         data = legos)
Warning: Removed 71 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

gf_boxplot(Packaging ~ Price,
         color = ~Availability,
         alpha = 0.3,
         scales = 'free',
         data = legos)

Model

lego_model <- lm(Price ~ Year + 
                   Pieces + Minifigures + 
                   Packaging*Availability+
                   Theme + Subtheme,
                 data = legos)
summary(lego_model)

```{r, make-lego-data, include = FALSE, eval = FALSE}
library(lego)
legos <- legosets |>
  rename(Price = USD_MSRP) |>
  select(-GBP_MSRP, -CAD_MSRP, -EUR_MSRP, -Image_URL) |>
  mutate(Minifigures = ifelse(is.na(Minifigures), 0, Minifigures)) |>
  arrange(Year, Theme, Subtheme, Name)

write_csv(legos, '../../../../academic-website/static/data/legos.csv')
```

# Data

The dataset for today gives details on `price` and other characteristics
of 6172 Lego toy sets, including the number of `Pieces` and
`Minifigures` inside and the `Year` they were created, as well as the
`Name`, `Theme`, `Subtheme` and `Item_Number` of each set.

In case you don't know the joy of lego, below is a minifigure sitting on
a vehicle made of lego bricks and pieces:


# Analysis to Critique

```{r, message = FALSE}
legos <- read_csv('https://sldr.netlify.app/data/legos.csv') |>
  mutate(Theme = factor(Theme),
         Subtheme = factor(Subtheme))
```

```{r}
gf_boxplot(Price ~ factor(Year), 
         alpha = 0.1,
         data = legos) |>
  gf_theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 70))

gf_point(Price ~ Minifigures, 
         alpha = 0.1,
         data = legos)

gf_point(Price ~ Pieces,
         color = ~Availability,
         alpha = 0.3,
         scales = 'free',
         data = legos)

gf_boxplot(Packaging ~ Price,
         color = ~Availability,
         alpha = 0.3,
         scales = 'free',
         data = legos)
```

## Model

```{r}
lego_model <- lm(Price ~ Year + 
                   Pieces + Minifigures + 
                   Packaging*Availability+
                   Theme + Subtheme,
                 data = legos)
summary(lego_model)
car::Anova(lego_model)
```

## Assessment

```{r}
gf_point(resid(lego_model) ~ 
           fitted(lego_model),
         alpha = 0.1) 
gf_qq(~resid(lego_model)) |>
  gf_qqline()
gf_acf(~lego_model)
```
